B. Hover & Selection States

Card Hover: When a specific card is hovered:

It scales up to 1.2x.

Its rotation resets to 0° for legibility.

It gains the highest z-index in the hand.

Drag-to-Play:

Dragging a card out of the hand and across a Y-axis threshold transitions it from Screen Space to Canvas Space.

The card loses its rotation and snaps to the cursor for placement on the table.

2. The Deck (Canvas Layer)
The Deck is an object situated on the infinite canvas.

A. Appearance

Stack Logic: A visual stack of card backs. We should use our card components for this. This should be similar to how we do the graveyard stack.


B. Floating Action Buttons (Left to Right)

Buttons appear on hover or selection, arranged from least to most frequent usage:

Mill 1: (skull icon) Moves the top card to the Graveyard.

Shuffle: (shuffle icon) Randomizes the deck array with a "shake" animation.

Draw 7: (hand icon) Batch moves 7 cards from the Deck array to the Hand state.

Draw 1: (plus icon) Moves the top card from the Deck to the Hand.

C. Tucking (Drop-Zone)

When a card is dragged over the deck, two glass-button zones appear:

Top: Releasing here places the card at index 0.

Bottom: Releasing here places the card at index last.

3. Hotkeys (Logic Only)
These actions trigger instantly when the relevant object is hovered or selected. No UI labels are required.

S: Shuffle Deck.

D: Draw 1 card (moves from Deck to Hand).

E: Send to Graveyard.

[: (During drag over deck) Place on bottom.

]: (During drag over deck) Place on top.

4. Technical Implementation Notes
Coordinate Conversion: Use screenToCanvas logic for the hand-to-table transition to ensure cards land exactly where the cursor is pointing regardless of zoom level.

Animations: Use spring physics for the hand arc and the hover scaling to maintain the tactile feel of the multiplayer canvas.